       ((COMMAND DESCRIPTION))

            The program will prompt for a device name which must be of the form
       FTAN  (Fast TApe) where N is a drive number.  Next the program will type
       the tracks and density available for that device.  When using a 9  track
       drive (on most PDP-10 tape jobs), then a density of 1600 or 6250 bpi can
       be used.  The default density should be 6250.  For each job,  TITO  will
       also  supply  a  device name which will appear on any directory listings
       for files written on the tape.  This feature can  be  used  1)  to  tell
       where the file was written;  (2) to read files written on a badly skewed
       drive;  (3) to indicate that a particular tape  drive  is  compatibility
       error prone and should be written up for NOVADYNE (FSC) to check out.

            All TITO commands and keyword modifiers may be abbreviated  to  the
       mininum  number  of  characters required to make the the command unique.
       For example, DIRECTORY  may  be  abbreviated  "DI"  and  DEVICE  may  be
       abbreviated   "DE".   TITO  will  always  inform  the  operator  if  the
       abbreviation is not unique, for example, the ambiguous abbreviation "D".

            The HELP command lists in summary form the program commands and the
       purpose  of  each.   In  addition,  Help may be typed in the middle of a
       multipart command to obtain the options that apply.

                             COMMAND FORMAT PARTS
                             --------------------

            The most often used commands in TITO are STORE,  RESTORE,  GET  and
       DIRECTORY.   There  are three general parts to TITO command format:  the
       verb, the object and the modifier.  STORE uses  all  three  parts  while
       RESTORE, GET and DIRECTORY use the first two parts.

                                      1.
       The first part of  each  command  is  the  verb  (STORE,  RESTORE,  GET,
       DIRECTORY).

          STORE  is  used  to  write  files   on   tape   and   requires   tape
          initialization.   It  is  used for customer tapes, backups, all files
          and transfers.

          RESTORE retrieves files from tape and places them in  their  original
          directories, unless some form of translation is used.

          GET functions the same as restore, except that  the  tape  files  are
          written  to  the TITO user's directory.  This in effect, is usually a
          translation from any tape user into directory (OPER) on disk.

          DIRECTORY is used to create a listing of file names  and  other  info
          from  a  specified  magtape.   Unless some form of the COF command is
          used, the tape directory will output on the terminal.





