                             THE CUT AFTER COMMAND
                             ---------------------

            The CUT AFTER command takes the form CUT AFTER FILENAME and can  be
       used  to  redefine logical End Of Tape (EOT).  It positions the tape out
       after the specified filename and writes a dummy saveset  trailer  record
       and  two  filemarks.   The  tape  is  then  positioned  between  the two
       filemarks with the logical EOT flag set, so that an APPEND at this point
       initializes the tape for writing without moving the tape.

            Since CUT AFTER is a very dangerous command, the following approach
       should  be  understood  to  avoid  losing  tape files due to positioning
       errors.

                           BACKUP AND ALL-FILE TAPES
                           -------------------------

            Don't use the "CUT AFTER" command to fix  an  aborted  "BACKUP"  or
       "ALL-FILE"  tape.   Run a full directory to the line printer;  determine
       the last "GOOD" tape position;  and, write  the  information  about  the
       last  good  tape position on the directory.  Use another tape to restart
       the "BACKUP" or "ALL-FILE", starting with  the  last  full  user  stored
       before the previous tape aborted.  

                                CUSTOMER TAPES
                                --------------

            When a customer tape aborts and doesn't have a logical "EOT" it  is
       necessary  to  use the "CUT AFTER" command.  First, run a full directory
       of the tape to the line printer  and  determine  the  last  "GOOD"  tape
       position.   Don't  use  the  "WHERE"  command  to determine correct tape
       position (it is UNTRUSTWORTHY).  Before using the "CUT  AFTER"  command,
       make  sure  the  tape  is  rewound  using "RWNW" and then issue the "CUT
       AFTER" command.  Be very careful that the correct  file  name  and  tape
       position  are correct before confirming the "CUT AFTER" command.  (Refer
       to "CONTINUING ON MULTIPLE TAPES" paragraph).

            There may be a noticeable delay between the  time  the  command  is
       given and the time the program asks for the tape pos.  range.  The delay
       is the time it takes TITO to locate a file header record on tape.


                                         NOTE

           See RESTARTING ALLFILES AND DAILY BACKUPS section for examples.








