       ERRORS AND RECOVERIES       ______ ___ __________

            A.  OUTPUT ERROR RECOVERY.  If a  write  error  is  encountered,  a
       section  of  blank tape enough to cover the size of the failed record is
       written onto the tape and the record is re-written.   If  the  retry  is
       unsuccessful,  then  another  section  of blank tape is written, and the
       record  is  tried  once  again.   If  this  cycle  finally  succeeds  in
       successfully  writing the record before OECMAX tries (currently 20 tries
       is the default) then the SAVE will  proceed  normally.   Otherwise,  the
       OPERATOR  is  asked to set the tape aside and mount a new tape, at which
       point the SAVE is restarted from there.  The only problem with this is -
       30 pages are lost and there's a good chance the tape won't verify.  If a
       lot of "DATA WRITE ERRORS" output, and the recovery was  "UNSUCCESSFUL",
       abort the job and start over with a "new" tape.

            The header record for each tape is actually read back after  it  is
       written to ensure that it made it out to the tape successfully.

            B.  INPUT ERROR RECOVERY.  On input, if an I/O error or consistency
       error  (bad  record  sequence number, bad prologue code) is encountered,
       the tape is searched backwards for the last good record.  If it  is  not
       found,  the tape is searched forwards for the first good record that can
       be found.  If it is found, a message stating what  the  last  disk  page
       restored or verified is printed.  The tape is then searched for the next
       good record.  If it is not found on  the  remainder  of  the  tape,  the
       OPERATOR  is  asked  to mount the next tape (if one exists).  Otherwise,
       the restore continues from the record that was found.

            C.  FATAL TAPE  OUTPUT  ERRORS.   Tape  should  be  given  to  Tape
       Librarian  for salvage or for scrapping.  Another tape should be made to
       take its place in the set.

            D.  TAPE OVERWRITES.  ASP will not allow a tape to  be  overwritten
       during a given ASP SAVE RUN if the HEADER on that tape indicates that it
       has been written during the run.  Should the occasion  arise,  an  ERROR
       message will output.  

            E.  OECMAX AND SRCLEN COMMANDS.  These commands set the  number  of
       times  an  output  record is tried to be written out before asking for a
       new tape, and the number of records to be search in input error recovery
       for a good record in the forward direction.  UNDER NORMAL CIRCUMSTANCES,
       THESE COMMANDS SHOULD NOT BE USED.










