       II.  Definitions

       The  following  definitions  should  be  helpful  in  understanding  the
       information that must be supplied to MAGCON.

       BLOCK

       A block pertains to a set of one or more records which MAGCON deals with
       as a unit.  On a tape, this will be the same as a physical record.

       LOGICAL RECORD

       A record refers to a contiguous set of characters which may be delimited
       by  a  CR-LF  sequence  or be defined by a character count.  A record is
       artificially defined;  it has no relationship to the device.

       BLOCK FACTOR

       This refers to the number of records contained in a block.   This  is  a
       value that the user of MAGCON must supply for tape files.  Blocking, the
       grouping of records together in a block involves a special structure  or
       meaning  in  only  two  cases.   One is the special block structure of a
       VEBCDIC file, and the other is the separation  of  HPASCII  blocks  with
       blank tape.  (See also Section 5.)

       UNBLOCKED TAPE

       In this context, an unblocked tape will refer to one whose block  factor
       is one.

       PHYSICAL RECORD

       A physical record is device dependent and refers to the smallest unit of
       data  that  can  be  processed  by  the hardware (128 words for disk, 80
       columns for card reader, the data between gaps for magnetic tape).   The
       blocks  and  records  mentioned  above may cross the boundaries of these
       physical records.

       CHARACTER OR BYTE

       The number of bits forming a character or byte is dependent on the  mode
       of  the  data.   If one is reading an EBCDIC tape, the character size of
       the input is considered to be eight bits.  If operating in  image  mode,
       the byte size dealt with is a whole word, 36 bits.

       INDUSTRY TAPE

       An industry tape  or  industry  compatible  tape  refers  to  one  whose
       character  size  is  eight  bits  and  which can be read or written four
       characters at a time (in 32 bit words).




       BTNA TAPE PROCEDURES
       REVISION 2; 10/21/93
                                                                        Page 47
MAGCON


       EOF MARK

       An EOF mark follows every file on a magnetic tape.   It  consists  of  a
       record  containing  an  octal 17 (for 7-track tapes) or an octal 23 (for
       9-track tapes).

       EOT MARK

       MAGCON does not write any special end of tape mark.








































