                                 PIP SWITCHES
                                 --- --------

       Any of the many options available in PIP may be selected  by  use  of  a
       switch.   Switches  that  do  not  reference magtape are preceded in the
       command string with a slash  (/);   magtape  switches  are  enclosed  in
       parenthesis  and must be typed immediately following the device to which
       they refer.  If more than on switch is used on either the destination of
       source  halves  of  the command string they are enclosed in parenthesis.
       Below is a list of PIP switches that are most  often  used.   (The  full
       list can be found in the document mentioned above.)

        MAGTAPE
        SWITCH           EFFECT
        ------           ------

        (M6)             Set tape density at 6250 BPI (9TRK default)
        (M1)             Set tape density at 1600 BPI
        (M8)             Set tape density at 800 BPI (7TRK default)
        (M5)             Set tape density at 556 BPI
        (ME)             Set parity even (odd parity is the default)
        (MA)             Advance the tape 1 file
        (M#nA)           Advance the tape n (some number) files
        (MB)             Backspace the tape 1 file
        (M#nB)           Backspace the tape n files
        (MW)             Rewind the tape
        (MT)             Skip to the logical END-OF-TAPE
        (MF)             Mark an END-OF-FILE

        NON-MAGTAPE
        SWITCH           EFFECT
        -----------      ------

        /B               Initialize devices in BINARY MODE; transfer
                         data one word at a time, no interpretation.
        /C               Delete trailing spaces; convert multiple spaces
                         to tabs.
        /E               Replace chars. 73 thru 80 with spaces (mainly
                         used with CDR).
        /G               Ignore (skip over) all I/O errors.
        /H               Initialize devices in IMAGE BINARY MODE.
        /I               Initialize devices in IMAGE MODE.
        /L               List a directory of the source device.
        /N               Delete sequence numbers from source file.
        /O               Insert sequence numbers at the beginning of
                         each line.  Start with 00000, increment by 1.





